<h1>Short-Term Incentives and Strategic Distortion</h1>

<p>
<b>Manish Meena</b><br>
Indian School of Business Hyderabad | IIT Gandhinagar | Loughborough University
</p>

<div class="section">
<h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>
This study investigates how short-term performance incentives shape micro-level decision-making and generate inefficiencies through distorted effort allocation. Leveraging ball-by-ball IPL data (2008–2025), the study constructs probabilistic measures of intent and context-adjusted expected performance.
</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p>
Modern organizations rely on short-term performance metrics, which may distort behavior toward visible outcomes rather than optimal decisions. This study uses IPL as a high-frequency decision environment.
</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Theoretical Framework</h2>
<p>
Grounded in multi-tasking theory and career concerns, agents prioritize observable outputs, leading to inefficient effort allocation and excessive risk-taking.
</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Research Questions</h2>
<p>
1. Do short-term incentives affect micro-level decision-making?<br>
2. Do such behaviors reduce aggregate efficiency?
</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Empirical Strategy</h2>

<p>Expected runs model:</p>

\[
E(Runs_{ibt} | Context_{bt}) = f(Context_{bt})
\]

<p>Residual definition:</p>

\[
Residual_{ibt} = Runs_{ibt} - E(Runs_{ibt} | Context_{bt})
\]

<p>Decomposition:</p>

\[
Residual^+ = max(Residual, 0), \quad Residual^- = min(Residual, 0)
\]

</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Intent Model</h2>

\[
Intent_{ibt} = P(AggressiveAction | Outcome_{ibt}, Context_{bt})
\]

</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Fixed Effects Model</h2>

\[
Intent_{ibt} = \beta_1 ContractYear_{it} + \beta_2 X_{ibt} + \alpha_i + \gamma_t + \epsilon_{ibt}
\]

</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Regression Discontinuity Design</h2>

\[
Intent_{ibt} = \alpha + \tau \cdot 1(Score_{it} \geq 50) + f(Score_{it}) + \epsilon_{ibt}
\]

</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Aggregate Outcome Model</h2>

\[
WPA_{ibt} = \delta \cdot Incentive_{ibt} + \beta X_{ibt} + \epsilon_{ibt}
\]

</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Expected Contribution</h2>
<p>
Provides micro-level causal evidence on incentive distortion and introduces a probabilistic intent framework.
</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>
The study highlights how observable performance metrics can distort decision-making and reduce efficiency.
</p>
</div>

